Deep 7 Shark Depredation Investigation

Meg Oshima

10/21/2021

Data structure

The data used in this analysis was requested from WPacFIN and is the FRS dataset from 2002 to 2021. Depredation data was not collected until Oct.1, 2002. The data are filtered to include only areas fished around the main Hawaiian Islands (area = MHI) and the deep 7 and Uku species. 15 gear-types are recorded, but the majority of the records are for gear 3 (n = 126,045).

QA/QC

Some issues within the dataset are:

  • instances of catch = 0, number_lost_to_predator = 0, and released = 0, but weight != 0. Recommend removing these records
fished Sp caught number_lost_to_predator release lbs
2002-10-29 Opakapaka 0 0 0 15.6
2002-11-03 Lehi 0 0 0 10.2
2002-11-23 Onaga 0 0 0 108.0
2002-12-21 Opakapaka 0 0 0 51.0
2003-01-07 Opakapaka 0 0 0 33.9
2003-01-09 Opakapaka 0 0 0 59.5


  • instances of catch is NA but number_lost_to_predator and lbs > 0. Would this be cases of the fishermen guessing at the weight that the lost fish were? Recommend removing these records unless more information is known.


tripID Sp caught lbs number_lost_to_predator release predator

22540_2811_2010-12-24 Opakapaka NA 150 20 0 Shark (Misc.)

  • instances of catch being NA (nrow = 379). Could assume NA (blank field) would be 0 catch.

Who is reporting depredation?

13% of all trips reported some loss of catch due to predators. Out of the 2390 unique fishing licenses, 170 have reported more than 10 instances with fish lost to predator over the entire time period and 38 fishers have reported more than 50 instances of fish lost to predator over the entire time period. The max number of reports by one license ID is 465 The mean number of trips with fish reported lost to predators is 376.79 trips per year.

Depredation Over Time

The proportion of catch lost to predators for the three main species that experience depredation (Opaka, Onaga, and Uku) is shown in the figure above. The proportion \(P\) is calculated by \(P = D_y/(D_y + C_y + R_y)\) where \(D_y\) is the total number of fish per species lost to predators in year \(y\), \(C_y\) is the total number of fish per species caught in year \(y\), and \(R_y\) is the number released in year \(y\). Note: most release is 0 so there is minimal difference between including and excluding released but included it to be consistent with other studies.

Spatial trends are not consistent among species. For Onaga and Uku, the highest percent of catch lost to depredation (11% and 8% respectively) is at Penguin Banks area but for Opakapaka and Lehi, the highest depredation is off Ohau (8% and 6% respectively). Ehu and Gindai also experience the highest depredation rates at Penguin Banks (2.5% and 1.6% respectively), and Hapuupuu and Kalekale experience highest depredation rates off Kauai.

Depredation by Trip Attributes

Gear Type

Gear types 3 (deep-sea handline), 6 (trolling), 9 (Palu Ahi, tuna handline), and 10 (casting) have the highest proportions of catch lost to predators. For gear 6, there were 5 individual fishing trips recorded using that gear type in 2003 (n = 1) and 2004 (n = 4). The species caught on those trips with gear 6 included Onaga (n = 5), Uku (n = 3), and Lehi (n = 2) and with only 1 Onaga reported as lost to a predator. Gear type 3 is the most commonly used and catches were highest for this gear for all species. With gear 9, Uku, Opakapaka, and Lehi catches were highest (n = 4389, n = 3772, and n = 2779 respectively) but Onaga had the highest proportion of catch lost to predators (prop_dep = 0.0897). Gear 10 caught Ehu, Gindai, Hapuupuu, Kalekale, Lehi, Onaga, Opakapaka, Uku with the majority being Uku. The species that experienced the highest proportion of catch lost to depredation was Kalekale, with 539 fish lost to a predator. With gear 10, the proportion of Uku catch lost to predators was 0.0406.

Depth

For all instances where depth (beginning [blue dots] or ending [red dots]) was recorded, there were no records of fish being lost to predators.

Wind Speed

For all instances where wind speed was recorded, there were no records of fish being lost to predators.
